03567nam a22005775i 9780292757202DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211988txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927572027 a10.7560/7761352doi  a(DE-B1597)586485  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a364.1/066/09794941 aVigil, James Diego, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBarrio Gangs :bStreet Life and Identity in Southern California /cJames Diego Vigil. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1988  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Ecological and Socioeconomic Background to Emergence of Street Gangs -- t3. Sociocultural Factors in the Choloization of the Mexican American Youth Population -- t4. Four Life Histories—Wizard, Geronimo, Freddie, and Henry -- t5. The Gang Subculture as a Lifeway: Structure, Process, and Form -- t6. The Notorious Side of the Gang Subculture -- t7. Psychodynamics of Gangs -- t8. Conclusion -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWithin the Mexican American barrios of Los Angeles, gang activity, including crime and violent acts, has grown and flourished. In the past, community leaders and law enforcement officials have approached the problem, not as something that needs to be understood, but only as something to be gotten rid of. Rejecting that approach, James D. Vigil asserts that only by understanding the complex factors that give birth and persistence to gangs can gang violence be ended. Drawing on many years of experience in the barrios as a youth worker, high school teacher, and researcher, Vigil identifies the elements from which gangs spring: isolation from the dominant culture, poverty, family stress and crowded households, peer pressure, and the adolescent struggle for self-identity. Using interviews with actual gang members, he reveals how the gang often functions as parent, school, and law enforcement in the absence of other role models in the gang members' lives. And he accounts for the longevity of gangs, sometimes over decades, by showing how they offer barrio youth a sense of identity and belonging nowhere else available.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292757202423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292757202/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK